## Part 5: Kubernetes

### Core concepts
Node        a server in your cluster
Cluster     group of nodes managed together
Pod         smallest unit — wraps one or more containers
Deployment  ensures N replicas always running
Service     stable address routing to healthy pods
Namespace   logical grouping — like folders

### deployment.yaml
apiVersion: apps/v1
kind: Deployment
metadata:
  name: flask-app
spec:
  replicas: 3
  selector:
    matchLabels:
      app: flask-app
  template:
    metadata:
      labels:
        app: flask-app
    spec:
      containers:
        - name: flask-app
          image: my-flask-app:latest
          imagePullPolicy: Never
          ports:
            - containerPort: 5000
          livenessProbe:
            httpGet:
              path: /health
              port: 5000
            initialDelaySeconds: 5
            periodSeconds: 10
          readinessProbe:
            httpGet:
              path: /health
              port: 5000
            initialDelaySeconds: 3
            periodSeconds: 5
          resources:
            requests:
              memory: "64Mi"
              cpu: "100m"
            limits:
              memory: "128Mi"
              cpu: "200m"

### service.yaml
apiVersion: v1
kind: Service
metadata:
  name: flask-app-service
spec:
  selector:
    app: flask-app
  ports:
    - protocol: TCP
      port: 80
      targetPort: 5000
  type: NodePort

### Key kubectl commands
kubectl apply -f k8s/deployment.yaml    create/update deployment
kubectl apply -f k8s/service.yaml       create/update service
kubectl get pods                         list pods
kubectl get deployments                  list deployments
kubectl describe pod pod-name           detailed info
kubectl logs pod-name                   see logs
kubectl delete pod pod-name             delete (K8s replaces it)
kubectl rollout status deployment/name  watch rollout
kubectl rollout undo deployment/name    rollback instantly

minikube start --driver=docker          start local cluster
minikube service service-name --url     get URL to access app

### Self-healing demo
kubectl delete pod flask-app-xxxxx
kubectl get pods
# New pod automatically created to replace it

### Rolling update (zero downtime)
kubectl set image deployment/flask-app flask-app=my-flask-app:v2
kubectl rollout status deployment/flask-app
# Pods replaced one at a time — app stays online

### Rollback
kubectl rollout undo deployment/flask-app
# Instantly back to previous version

### Probes explained
livenessProbe   is the container alive? kill and restart if failing
readinessProbe  is the container ready? withhold traffic until passing

