## Part 6: Terraform

### Key concepts
Provider    plugin that talks to a service (GitHub, AWS, GCP)
Resource    piece of infrastructure you want to exist
Variable    input parameter — keeps secrets out of code
State       terraform's record of what exists (.tfstate files)
Plan        shows what would change — without doing it
Apply       executes the changes

### main.tf
terraform {
  required_providers {
    github = {
      source  = "integrations/github"
      version = "~> 6.0"
    }
  }
}

provider "github" {
  token = var.github_token
  owner = var.github_owner
}

resource "github_repository" "flask_app" {
  name        = "my-flask-app"
  description = "Flask CI/CD demo with GitHub Actions, Docker, and Kubernetes"
  visibility  = "public"
  delete_branch_on_merge = true
}

resource "github_branch_protection" "main" {
  repository_id = github_repository.flask_app.node_id
  pattern       = "main"
  required_status_checks {
    strict   = true
    contexts = ["build-and-test", "docker-build"]
  }
}

### variables.tf
variable "github_token" {
  description = "GitHub personal access token"
  type        = string
  sensitive   = true
}

variable "github_owner" {
  type = string
}

### terraform.tfvars (NEVER COMMIT)
github_owner = "khangusername"
github_token = "ghp_xxxxxxxxxxxx"

### Key commands
terraform init      download providers (run once per project)
terraform plan      preview changes — ALWAYS run before apply
terraform apply     execute changes — type "yes" to confirm
terraform destroy   delete all managed infrastructure
terraform import resource_type.name existing_id

### Plan symbols
+    will be created
~    will be updated in place
-    will be destroyed
-/+  will be destroyed then recreated

