## Part 9: Interview Answers

### "Walk me through your CI/CD experience"
I built a GitHub Actions pipeline for a Python Flask app. It runs on every push —
pytest with 75% coverage enforcement, flake8 linting, black formatting checks,
bandit security scanning, and pip-audit CVE detection. After all checks pass it
builds a Docker image tagged with the commit SHA, verifies the container starts
and responds to health checks, then automatically deploys to Render and confirms
the live URL is healthy. The whole chain from push to production takes under 90 seconds.

### "Tell me about debugging a pipeline failure"
My first pipeline run hit four consecutive failures. Coverage threshold was too
high for untestable code — I lowered it and explained why. Bandit flagged 0.0.0.0
binding — I added nosec with the specific check ID after understanding the risk.
Then pip-audit found real CVEs in Flask, pytest, and python-dotenv — I upgraded
all three to the patched versions.

### "What do you know about Docker?"
I containerized a Flask app with layer caching optimization — copying requirements.txt
separately before application code so pip only re-runs when dependencies change.
Images are tagged with commit SHA for traceability. .dockerignore excludes venv
and .env to keep images lean and secure.

### "What is Kubernetes?"
Container orchestration. I deployed a Flask app with 3 replicas, configured
liveness and readiness probes so Kubernetes automatically replaces unhealthy pods
and withholds traffic from pods that aren't ready. Demonstrated self-healing and
zero-downtime rolling updates with kubectl rollout, and instant rollback with
kubectl rollout undo.

### "What is Terraform?"
Infrastructure as code. I used the GitHub provider to manage repository settings
and branch protection rules as code — version controlled, reviewable in PRs,
reproducible. I ran terraform plan before every apply and used terraform import
to bring an existing repo under management.

